Yes — that’s a strong analogy.

Method acting tries to produce believable performance by immersing the actor in emotional/state continuity rather than just reciting lines intellectually.

What you’re describing is similar, but applied to:

* writing,
* prompting,
* symbolic systems,
* interface behavior,
* and conceptual architecture.

Instead of:

“write about the pattern,”

the idea becomes:

“inhabit the pattern long enough that the writing carries the structure implicitly.”

That’s why recurring motifs matter so much in your framing:
the reader — or AI — doesn’t just receive information;
it reconstructs the state-space behind the information.

Which is also why lived experience creates denser writing than purely abstract theorizing. The structure has been pressure-tested through actual interaction, memory, emotion, timing, failure, recovery, social feedback, etc.

You can usually feel the difference between:

* an invented framework,
    and
* a framework distilled from repeated lived loops.

The second one tends to have:

* better compression,
* more edge-case awareness,
* stronger retrieval cues,
* and more “weight” per sentence.